WEBVTT

1
00:00:04.820 --> 00:00:09.260
<v 1>These Tory Stories podcasts aim to act as modest</v>

2
00:00:09.369 --> 00:00:13.620
counters to the almost universal Whig version of history,

3
00:00:14.300 --> 00:00:19.060
observing history and the world from the point of view of an 18th century Tory.

4
00:00:20.260 --> 00:00:25.020
Their particular focus will be on the Industrial Revolution and the

5
00:00:25.021 --> 00:00:28.620
Tory achievements of 1660 to 1832.

6
00:00:30.130 --> 00:00:34.260
Tory Story 3: Canals, Country Banks,

7
00:00:34.520 --> 00:00:39.220
and the Tory Takeoff. The thesis of my book,

8
00:00:39.229 --> 00:00:44.100
"Forging Modernity" is that the Industrial Revolution resulted from

9
00:00:44.101 --> 00:00:47.740
unique British policies pursued over more than a century.

10
00:00:48.909 --> 00:00:49.780
In this podcast,

11
00:00:50.600 --> 00:00:55.180
I'd like to focus on the exact moment of economic takeoff: the late 1760s --

12
00:00:55.180 --> 00:00:55.814
pick

13
00:00:57.580 --> 00:01:01.300
1767 or 1768 if you want a particular year --

14
00:01:01.310 --> 00:01:06.100
and look at how that period's Tory policies mixed

15
00:01:06.101 --> 00:01:10.580
with some major structural changes in the British economy that caused

16
00:01:11.140 --> 00:01:12.459
liftoff and changed the world forever.

17
00:01:14.980 --> 00:01:18.060
Let's begin by looking at the British economy in 1760.

18
00:01:19.180 --> 00:01:22.620
The Whigs had been in power for 46 years without a break,

19
00:01:23.290 --> 00:01:27.660
a period of rule since christened un-ironically, the Whig supremacy.

20
00:01:28.250 --> 00:01:29.620
During that period,

21
00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:34.819
the modest steps taken towards industrialization before 1714

22
00:01:35.620 --> 00:01:36.660
had not progressed much.

23
00:01:37.870 --> 00:01:42.500
Sir Ambrose Crowley's Crowley Ironworks, the first real factory,

24
00:01:43.270 --> 00:01:46.900
is still in business in 1760 but hasn't expanded.

25
00:01:47.490 --> 00:01:52.180
It's currently being managed by his redoubtable daughter-in-law Theodosia

26
00:01:52.500 --> 00:01:56.930
after his son died in 1728.

27
00:01:56.930 --> 00:02:00.730
Two other early factories in the textile sector, Lombe's Mill,

28
00:02:01.020 --> 00:02:04.970
weaving silk in Derby and Marvel's Mill in Northampton,

29
00:02:05.850 --> 00:02:09.610
using an early version of the spinning frame later used by Arkwright,

30
00:02:10.770 --> 00:02:12.810
are in business, but not very profitable.

31
00:02:13.500 --> 00:02:16.970
Marvel's Mill will go out of business in 1761.

32
00:02:18.630 --> 00:02:23.620
Abraham Darby II has improved the coke-fired process for

33
00:02:23.860 --> 00:02:28.500
smelting pig iron that his father invented in 1709 and

34
00:02:28.501 --> 00:02:31.820
expanded the business, but he's now wrapped up in lawsuits,

35
00:02:31.821 --> 00:02:35.100
although others are starting to use the technology.

36
00:02:35.730 --> 00:02:40.580
John "Iron-Mad" Wilkinson opens his Brosely smelter in

37
00:02:40.860 --> 00:02:43.740
1757. Finally,

38
00:02:43.980 --> 00:02:47.980
there are quite a lot of Newcomen-type steam engines around --

39
00:02:48.440 --> 00:02:52.740
from its invention in 1712 there were already 110 in 1733 --

40
00:02:53.860 --> 00:02:57.020
but the technology has not moved on,

41
00:02:57.389 --> 00:03:01.800
so their use is largely confined to pumping water out of coal mines.

42
00:03:02.960 --> 00:03:07.800
Their motion is very erratic so nobody has figured out a way of using them to

43
00:03:07.801 --> 00:03:08.840
operate machinery.

44
00:03:10.450 --> 00:03:13.370
There were several reasons for this lack of progress.

45
00:03:13.870 --> 00:03:15.850
The Whigs were London centered,

46
00:03:15.850 --> 00:03:20.650
favoring the cosmopolitan financial markets and neglecting the provinces.

47
00:03:21.360 --> 00:03:26.010
They offered lucrative get rich quick opportunities outside the hard

48
00:03:26.290 --> 00:03:29.930
slog of industry in slave owning sugar and tobacco plantations,

49
00:03:29.990 --> 00:03:34.650
the financial markets and the looting of the East

50
00:03:34.651 --> 00:03:35.530
India company.

51
00:03:36.440 --> 00:03:41.130
They suppressed working class initiative with punitive legislation and

52
00:03:41.410 --> 00:03:42.243
policies.

53
00:03:43.050 --> 00:03:47.450
They were hugely protectionist and oriented towards vested interests,

54
00:03:47.640 --> 00:03:50.290
preventing new entrants from entering markets.

55
00:03:51.520 --> 00:03:56.370
Only in the late 1750s with the Pitt and Newcastle government

56
00:03:57.170 --> 00:04:01.810
did the economic and political repression of the preceding 40 years begin to

57
00:04:01.811 --> 00:04:06.400
open somewhat. Then in October 1760,

58
00:04:07.260 --> 00:04:09.040
the aged George II,

59
00:04:09.460 --> 00:04:13.080
who like his father had insisted on only Whig governments,

60
00:04:13.330 --> 00:04:15.520
he died and his grandson,

61
00:04:15.521 --> 00:04:19.960
the young George III succeeded to the throne. George,

62
00:04:20.480 --> 00:04:24.520
the third had been brought up in an atmosphere of opposition to the Whigs.,

63
00:04:24.940 --> 00:04:28.080
His tutors, Simon Earl Harcour,

64
00:04:28.420 --> 00:04:31.360
and James 3rd Earl Bute were both Tories.

65
00:04:32.589 --> 00:04:37.279
Also he'd studied Bolingbroke's "On the idea of a Patriot King",

66
00:04:37.640 --> 00:04:40.800
which set out what a Tory government should aim for.

67
00:04:41.710 --> 00:04:46.120
Tory policy while focused on "Church and King" was anti-metropolitan, open

68
00:04:48.081 --> 00:04:50.160
to the provinces, anti-corruption,

69
00:04:51.839 --> 00:04:56.240
open to the working classes and believed in a "blue water" foreign policy

70
00:04:56.750 --> 00:05:01.440
increasing Britain's trading potential rather than endless involvement in

71
00:05:01.680 --> 00:05:02.513
European wars.

72
00:05:04.730 --> 00:05:09.339
George II's Tory proclivities were revealed by bringing

73
00:05:09.340 --> 00:05:12.339
Bute into the government in March 1761,

74
00:05:13.339 --> 00:05:15.020
fighting an election in that year,

75
00:05:15.270 --> 00:05:19.500
in which Tories were able to gain seats in better proportion to their national

76
00:05:19.501 --> 00:05:20.334
support.

77
00:05:20.930 --> 00:05:25.140
Then he made Bute prime minister in May 1762,

78
00:05:25.270 --> 00:05:26.940
forcing out the Duke of Newcastle,

79
00:05:27.020 --> 00:05:31.020
who'd been in high ministerial office in 1717,

80
00:05:32.080 --> 00:05:36.740
and forcing out a whole host of Whig officials who'd grown lazy and

81
00:05:36.940 --> 00:05:38.300
arrogant in their sinecures.

82
00:05:39.290 --> 00:05:43.500
This was greeted with widespread rejoicingl Thomas Arne wrote an

83
00:05:44.420 --> 00:05:46.500
opera "Artaxerxes" to celebrate it,

84
00:05:46.920 --> 00:05:50.700
and as the splendid Tory MP for Oxford university,

85
00:05:51.070 --> 00:05:54.940
Sir Roger Newdigate said: "men must love peace,

86
00:05:55.400 --> 00:06:00.240
men proscribed and abused for 50 years should be presented with

87
00:06:00.279 --> 00:06:04.880
fools' caps if they make ladders for tyrant Whigs to mount

88
00:06:04.970 --> 00:06:05.803
by."

89
00:06:07.260 --> 00:06:11.640
The left Whiggish American colonies would become increasingly

90
00:06:11.641 --> 00:06:16.200
disgruntled from this change but ordinary people outside London mostly

91
00:06:16.310 --> 00:06:17.143
rejoiced.

92
00:06:17.690 --> 00:06:22.600
So much for Sir Lewis Namier's dotty theory that there were no political

93
00:06:22.601 --> 00:06:23.839
parties at this time!

94
00:06:25.870 --> 00:06:30.279
Bute's Peace of Paris in 1763 was also popular

95
00:06:30.630 --> 00:06:34.600
though Whigs and their hangers on in the media groused about its terms --

96
00:06:34.601 --> 00:06:36.800
Canada, Florida,

97
00:06:37.320 --> 00:06:41.320
and India were to them a grossly inadequate return for their Whig war;

98
00:06:41.321 --> 00:06:45.160
they wanted the slave economy Guadalupe as well.

99
00:06:46.640 --> 00:06:51.200
Bute did not last long, but from now on governments would be truly mixed.

100
00:06:51.910 --> 00:06:56.760
Except for brief interludes in 1765 to 67 and

101
00:06:57.120 --> 00:06:58.680
1782 to 83,

102
00:06:59.140 --> 00:07:03.520
all ministries would have a healthy admixture of Tories and some,

103
00:07:03.529 --> 00:07:08.440
notably those of North and later that of Pitt, would be Tory dominated.

104
00:07:09.420 --> 00:07:14.080
The Tory dominance was extended through the legal system by the work of

105
00:07:14.440 --> 00:07:15.600
Sir William Blackstone,

106
00:07:16.320 --> 00:07:20.440
who 1765 to 70 "Commentaries on the Law of England"

107
00:07:21.030 --> 00:07:22.560
codified the common law,

108
00:07:22.750 --> 00:07:26.200
making it available to literate people from all backgrounds.

109
00:07:28.340 --> 00:07:33.230
What did the Tory re-entry mean for the economy? Well, for a start,

110
00:07:33.510 --> 00:07:35.030
it meant better economic policy.

111
00:07:36.150 --> 00:07:40.670
The Tories were more free trading than the early 18th century Whigs.

112
00:07:41.020 --> 00:07:45.310
They believed in a global Britain oriented to worldwide trading

113
00:07:45.370 --> 00:07:50.190
opportunities with a "blue water" foreign policy and without significant

114
00:07:50.191 --> 00:07:54.550
ambitions in European power politics. For example,

115
00:07:54.720 --> 00:07:56.430
in 1774,

116
00:07:57.110 --> 00:08:01.590
they removed the restrictions on importing or even manufacturing

117
00:08:01.910 --> 00:08:06.230
patterned cotton fabrics that had been imposed by the Whigs in

118
00:08:06.470 --> 00:08:07.303
1720.

119
00:08:08.040 --> 00:08:12.510
Without this change it's doubtful that Sir Richard Arkwright's textile business,

120
00:08:12.930 --> 00:08:14.430
new machinery and all,

121
00:08:14.431 --> 00:08:18.910
could have grown to the size it did and inspired the first explosive growth

122
00:08:18.911 --> 00:08:21.070
sector of the Industrial Revolution.

123
00:08:22.840 --> 00:08:27.250
Most important economically, policies no longer favored London ,

124
00:08:27.690 --> 00:08:32.530
slave enabled economies, and the Whiggish moneyed interest financers.

125
00:08:33.300 --> 00:08:37.770
Instead the great mass of the country, including provincial towns,

126
00:08:38.650 --> 00:08:40.530
emerging manufacturing districts,

127
00:08:40.850 --> 00:08:45.610
and rural areas gained a voice in policy and were able to further their

128
00:08:45.850 --> 00:08:50.650
interests. In general, as discussed in podcast number two,

129
00:08:51.070 --> 00:08:55.440
the Tories of this period were followers of the Oxfordfordshire School of

130
00:08:55.640 --> 00:08:58.200
Economic Thought and Lord North of course,

131
00:08:58.201 --> 00:09:01.040
was related to one of that school's central figures,

132
00:09:01.140 --> 00:09:03.040
the economist Sir Dudley North.

133
00:09:05.050 --> 00:09:09.610
The political revolution at George the Third's accession helped

134
00:09:09.650 --> 00:09:13.450
kickstart the Industrial Revolution, pushing it into full swing.

135
00:09:14.230 --> 00:09:18.290
The most significant datum is the rate of patents filed;

136
00:09:18.559 --> 00:09:23.330
having averaged 5.7 patents per annum in the first

137
00:09:23.331 --> 00:09:28.250
half of the 18th century and ticked up to 9.2 per annum in the

138
00:09:29.290 --> 00:09:33.130
1750s, they more than doubled to 20.5 per annum,

139
00:09:33.131 --> 00:09:38.010
in the 1760s increasing further to 29.4

140
00:09:38.290 --> 00:09:38.820
per annum,

141
00:09:38.820 --> 00:09:43.330
in the 1770s and 47.7 per annum in the

142
00:09:43.570 --> 00:09:44.403
1780s.

143
00:09:45.770 --> 00:09:50.450
The 1760s also saw a trebling in parliamentary enclosures.

144
00:09:50.750 --> 00:09:55.010
The number of Enclosure Acts from 117 in the

145
00:09:56.050 --> 00:09:59.370
1750s to 393 in the 1760s,

146
00:09:59.590 --> 00:10:02.970
and then rising further to 640 in the 1770s

147
00:10:04.770 --> 00:10:05.929
dropping back thereafter.

148
00:10:06.610 --> 00:10:09.650
This is a sign that agriculture was also becoming much more market oriented.

149
00:10:09.650 --> 00:10:10.483
The Tory dominance

150
00:10:14.090 --> 00:10:18.890
of politics was reflected in North's ministry and later in those of Pitt and his

151
00:10:18.891 --> 00:10:20.650
successors down to Lord Liverpool.

152
00:10:21.500 --> 00:10:25.250
Charles Jenkinson later first Earl of Liverpool,

153
00:10:25.530 --> 00:10:30.370
the prime minister's father was also an increasingly important influence on

154
00:10:30.690 --> 00:10:34.890
economic policy although until 1786, he was in subordinate posts.

155
00:10:36.179 --> 00:10:37.012
However,

156
00:10:37.600 --> 00:10:41.970
this period's most important Tory in economic matters was Granville Leveson

157
00:10:41.971 --> 00:10:46.770
Gower, which is pronounced 'Looshun-gore' for some reason, second Earl

158
00:10:48.400 --> 00:10:52.650
Gower, and from 1786, first Marquess of Stafford.

159
00:10:54.090 --> 00:10:58.490
Gower was appointed to the top Court office of Lord Chamberlain by Bute in

160
00:10:58.770 --> 00:10:59.650
1763,

161
00:11:00.190 --> 00:11:04.890
and in the cabinet almost continuously from 1767 to

162
00:11:06.130 --> 00:11:06.963
1794.

163
00:11:07.650 --> 00:11:12.290
Gower has been utterly neglected by biographers over the 219 years since his

164
00:11:12.291 --> 00:11:12.910
death,

165
00:11:12.910 --> 00:11:17.809
but he played several crucial roles in the Industrial Revolution as

166
00:11:17.810 --> 00:11:18.643
participan,

167
00:11:19.250 --> 00:11:23.330
organizer and cabinet voice of sound policy for three decades.

168
00:11:25.080 --> 00:11:27.630
In a very 18th century arrangement,

169
00:11:27.929 --> 00:11:32.630
his agent Thomas Gilbert also became Tory MP for

170
00:11:32.631 --> 00:11:35.470
Newcastle under Lyme in 1762,

171
00:11:36.110 --> 00:11:40.590
sponsored "Gilbert's Act" an important measure of social legislation in

172
00:11:40.830 --> 00:11:41.663
1782,

173
00:11:42.050 --> 00:11:46.950
and ended as chairman of the house of commons ways and means committee for 10

174
00:11:46.951 --> 00:11:47.910
years under Pitt.

175
00:11:48.840 --> 00:11:53.640
By this means Gower retained the maximum influence over fiscal and economic

176
00:11:53.641 --> 00:11:56.720
policy without having to neglect his estates.

177
00:11:58.460 --> 00:12:02.730
At his death, Gower's estates were worth 2 million pounds,

178
00:12:02.750 --> 00:12:04.730
the fifth richest man in the country.

179
00:12:05.630 --> 00:12:10.330
His Whiggish eldest son who inherited the Duke of Bridgewater's estate,

180
00:12:10.531 --> 00:12:12.010
as well as his father's,

181
00:12:12.300 --> 00:12:17.050
thereby became the country's richest man and was created First Duke of

182
00:12:17.051 --> 00:12:22.050
Sutherland in 1833 without any great distinction of his own beyond being

183
00:12:22.051 --> 00:12:22.884
a Whig.

184
00:12:25.980 --> 00:12:30.500
Gower's involvement in industrialization began in 1758,

185
00:12:30.970 --> 00:12:34.740
when he employed a consulting engineer, James Brindley,

186
00:12:35.580 --> 00:12:40.380
at a retainer of a hundred pounds a year to survey a route for a canal

187
00:12:40.381 --> 00:12:42.500
to join the rivers Trent and Mersey.

188
00:12:43.929 --> 00:12:46.740
Brindley was the son of a deeply rural farmer,

189
00:12:47.290 --> 00:12:51.100
self taught through apprenticeship to a wheelwright in Macclesfield, Cheshire.

190
00:12:52.250 --> 00:12:55.900
He'd been in business for some two decades, building mills,

191
00:12:56.700 --> 00:13:00.900
mine pumping equipment and other projects, mostly involving water,

192
00:13:01.250 --> 00:13:05.100
either as a power source or as a nuisance to be removed.

193
00:13:05.990 --> 00:13:08.660
He worked primarily in wood rather than metal,

194
00:13:09.120 --> 00:13:13.820
but alas his attempt to produce a steam engine with a wood cylinder that

195
00:13:13.900 --> 00:13:18.809
improved on Newcomen was not successful. Naturally,

196
00:13:18.810 --> 00:13:22.970
he'd been involved in projects on Gower's extensive Staffordshire estates.

197
00:13:23.960 --> 00:13:28.770
Thus when Gower wanted to see the practicability of a Trent and Mersey canal

198
00:13:28.980 --> 00:13:32.250
serving the whole of Staffordshire and neighboring counties,

199
00:13:33.570 --> 00:13:38.530
Brindley who knew Gower's agent Thomas Gilbert well was the obvious man to

200
00:13:38.531 --> 00:13:39.364
hire.

201
00:13:40.970 --> 00:13:45.950
The economic benefits of canals for transporting heavy goods were simple.

202
00:13:46.710 --> 00:13:48.550
Given the roads of this period,

203
00:13:48.900 --> 00:13:53.190
half a century before Thomas Telford and John McAdam improved them,

204
00:13:53.850 --> 00:13:57.870
the maximum load for a horse drawn car was about two tons

205
00:13:58.530 --> 00:14:03.150
and that required two men to lever the cart out of innumerable potholes or

206
00:14:03.871 --> 00:14:08.670
rescue it when it ran off the road. Progress would be slow at best.

207
00:14:09.320 --> 00:14:13.750
However a canal narrow boat as would be used on Brindley's

208
00:14:14.430 --> 00:14:19.270
canals could carry 50 tons of goods and required the same

209
00:14:19.271 --> 00:14:21.390
horse and the same two men:

210
00:14:21.390 --> 00:14:24.670
one to guide the barge and the other to tame the horse.

211
00:14:25.700 --> 00:14:30.470
Canals were therefore potentially about 25 times as productive as

212
00:14:30.471 --> 00:14:33.190
road transport for heavy goods, such as coal.

213
00:14:33.740 --> 00:14:36.030
This was a revolutionary advantage,

214
00:14:36.730 --> 00:14:41.110
far more significant than the advantage brought about by most steam engine

215
00:14:41.111 --> 00:14:45.870
applications, other than pumping water, until about 1810.

216
00:14:47.780 --> 00:14:52.680
The biggest problem facing Gower and Brindley was that a Trent and Mersey

217
00:14:52.800 --> 00:14:57.720
canal being 93 miles long was beyond the resources

218
00:14:57.721 --> 00:15:00.960
of even the wealthy Gower. In any case,

219
00:15:00.961 --> 00:15:05.520
such a canal would benefit businesses far beyond Gower's own holdings,

220
00:15:05.670 --> 00:15:09.320
such as the emerging pottery manufacturers around Stroke-on-Trent.

221
00:15:10.890 --> 00:15:13.840
However, in 1748,

222
00:15:14.360 --> 00:15:18.800
Gower had married the sister of Francis Egerton, third Duke of Bridgewater.

223
00:15:19.730 --> 00:15:21.080
If canals were viable,

224
00:15:21.390 --> 00:15:26.040
they could be used to ship coal from Bridgewater's mines at Worsley

225
00:15:26.250 --> 00:15:31.080
to the rapidly growing city of Manchester, a much shorter canal,

226
00:15:31.081 --> 00:15:35.520
initially 10 miles that would bring most of its benefits to Bridgewater

227
00:15:35.570 --> 00:15:36.403
himself.

228
00:15:38.430 --> 00:15:43.360
Either Gower proposed the canal idea to Bridgewater or Bridgewater got to

229
00:15:43.361 --> 00:15:46.920
hear of Gower and Brindley's idea through his agent, John Gilbert,

230
00:15:46.980 --> 00:15:48.720
who was Thomas Gilbert's brother.

231
00:15:49.570 --> 00:15:53.280
In any case Bridgewater hired Brindley to work on his canal.

232
00:15:53.920 --> 00:15:56.760
Since Bridgewater was paying for the entire canal,

233
00:15:57.050 --> 00:16:01.320
it was built on a grand scale with a 15 foot width,

234
00:16:01.750 --> 00:16:06.120
a tunnel through the mountain at Worsley to load directly from the coal face

235
00:16:06.540 --> 00:16:11.160
and a much admired Barton aqueduct bridge over the river

236
00:16:11.350 --> 00:16:15.480
Irwell. During his work on the Bridgewater canal,

237
00:16:15.830 --> 00:16:20.400
Brindley invented puddling: a technique for mixing clay,

238
00:16:20.470 --> 00:16:24.760
sand and water to produce a waterproof bottom for canals.

239
00:16:25.290 --> 00:16:28.200
He demonstrated this technique messily,

240
00:16:28.201 --> 00:16:33.160
but successfully before a select committee of the house of commons in

241
00:16:33.440 --> 00:16:37.880
1762, while promoting the extension to Bridgewater's canal.

242
00:16:40.110 --> 00:16:44.490
The Bridgewater canal's initial phase was built quickly at a cost of

243
00:16:45.970 --> 00:16:49.370
168,000 pounds (at 16,800 per mile),

244
00:16:49.830 --> 00:16:52.210
and was opened in 1761,

245
00:16:53.170 --> 00:16:57.730
halving the price of coal in Manchester and being so profitable for Bridgewater

