00:33:53.131 --> 00:33:55.290
we now call private banking for the very rich.

492
00:33:57.850 --> 00:34:00.210
By the Bank of England Act 1708,

493
00:34:00.740 --> 00:34:04.210
no bank other than the Bank of England was allowed to have more than six

494
00:34:04.211 --> 00:34:05.044
partners.

495
00:34:05.160 --> 00:34:09.969
This didn't matter to the Goldsmith bankers who became very rich and snooty

496
00:34:09.970 --> 00:34:13.130
like the merchant banks of 1914. However,

497
00:34:13.131 --> 00:34:17.610
there was a huge void in providing financial services to the gentry

498
00:34:17.611 --> 00:34:20.489
tradesmen and other ordinary people outside London.

499
00:34:21.330 --> 00:34:22.770
After 1750,

500
00:34:23.040 --> 00:34:27.450
this void began to be filled by the creation of local country banks.

501
00:34:28.610 --> 00:34:33.050
One such country bank, Smiths of Nottingham was founded in 1688,

502
00:34:33.190 --> 00:34:36.370
but there don't appear to have been any others before 1750.

503
00:34:37.290 --> 00:34:41.730
These country banks had a business mix like the old Scrivener

504
00:34:42.451 --> 00:34:46.410
bankers but were concentrated in one provincial town, their headquarters.

505
00:34:47.650 --> 00:34:51.969
They were typically set up by local attorneys with partners drawn from the most

506
00:34:51.969 --> 00:34:56.489
prosperous local tradesmen and had modest capital normally below 10,000 pounds.

507
00:34:59.670 --> 00:35:03.300
Country banks' legal setup affected how they did business.

508
00:35:03.690 --> 00:35:08.460
They could not grow much because their capital was so limited and until the

509
00:35:08.660 --> 00:35:13.460
1826 crisis each year's profits were normally paid out as dividends to partners.

510
00:35:14.130 --> 00:35:16.020
They did not have many posh,

511
00:35:16.021 --> 00:35:20.140
wealthy landowners as partners because of unlimited liability.

512
00:35:20.560 --> 00:35:25.260
The unhappy experience of two Scottish Dukes among

513
00:35:26.460 --> 00:35:30.980
114 partners of the Ayr bank (there was no partner limitation in Scotland)

514
00:35:31.520 --> 00:35:36.380
who were pursued until the 1820s by creditors from its collapse

515
00:35:36.381 --> 00:35:41.360
in 1772) showed the downside of being the richest partner in a

516
00:35:41.361 --> 00:35:42.280
bank that went wrong.

517
00:35:43.550 --> 00:35:47.719
They did no long term lending because the Usury Act of 1714

518
00:35:48.719 --> 00:35:50.719
prevented them from charging interest of more than five percent --

519
00:35:51.880 --> 00:35:54.560
no junk bond market therefore. However,

520
00:35:55.110 --> 00:35:57.239
unlike the American local banks,

521
00:35:57.240 --> 00:36:02.200
after the 1836 de-chartering of the second bank of the United States,

522
00:36:02.780 --> 00:36:06.080
the country banks' bank notes normally traded at par,

523
00:36:06.469 --> 00:36:08.200
even outside their region.

524
00:36:08.670 --> 00:36:13.200
This was achieved by each country bank employing a London correspondent

525
00:36:13.460 --> 00:36:17.640
who acted as a clearing house for its notes of banks from other regions.

526
00:36:19.219 --> 00:36:20.052
Overall,

527
00:36:20.500 --> 00:36:24.410
as well as providing services to private individuals and institutions,

528
00:36:25.370 --> 00:36:30.210
country banks provided a wide range of services to nascent industrialization

529
00:36:30.370 --> 00:36:34.530
which would've been greatly hindered by their absence. First,

530
00:36:34.531 --> 00:36:37.890
there was the simple matter of introductions to financing sources.

531
00:36:38.350 --> 00:36:41.770
The banks generally didn't provide venture capital directly,

532
00:36:41.830 --> 00:36:44.410
but their partners and wealthy customers might.

533
00:36:46.010 --> 00:36:50.770
Discounting bills of exchange and thereby providing liquidity

534
00:36:50.950 --> 00:36:53.170
was often the main introductory service,

535
00:36:53.510 --> 00:36:58.410
but paying wages to workers in local bank notes and providing receivables

536
00:36:58.411 --> 00:37:02.489
financing through discounting were all common. In addition,

537
00:37:02.490 --> 00:37:07.410
the country banker might provide inventory and other financing through overdraft

538
00:37:07.691 --> 00:37:12.250
facilities to the businesses owners generally secured by promisary notes

539
00:37:12.570 --> 00:37:17.489
often for double the amount of the loan facility or secured by mortgages,

540
00:37:17.570 --> 00:37:21.850
which were highly illiquid but represented a claim on an asset of real value.

541
00:37:23.180 --> 00:37:25.489
In one case, Praed and company of Truro,

542
00:37:26.580 --> 00:37:30.969
country bankers came to specialize in Watt steam engines

543
00:37:31.219 --> 00:37:34.130
pumping out Cornish tin and copper mines --

544
00:37:34.930 --> 00:37:39.130
an early example of effective equipment financing with relationships,

545
00:37:39.131 --> 00:37:41.250
with both the mines and Boulton and Watt.

546
00:37:42.219 --> 00:37:46.890
Finally country banks provided executor and trustee services when

547
00:37:47.490 --> 00:37:52.410
a proprietor died, facilitating the continuance of the business after his death.

548
00:37:53.000 --> 00:37:55.530
Knocking out the fly by night operations,

549
00:37:56.250 --> 00:38:00.969
there were by 1780 a couple of hundred solid country banks all run

550
00:38:00.989 --> 00:38:03.250
independently by different partner groups.

551
00:38:03.890 --> 00:38:06.610
Since there was no centralized credit training,

552
00:38:06.960 --> 00:38:11.370
each country bank did business in its own way with its own specialties.

553
00:38:12.050 --> 00:38:16.850
Providing an entrepreneur was not so eccentric as to setup his business where

554
00:38:16.851 --> 00:38:18.370
there was no local expertise,

555
00:38:18.610 --> 00:38:23.210
there were probably half a dozen country banks he could talk to within a day's

556
00:38:23.211 --> 00:38:26.370
horse ride, each of them doing business differently.

557
00:38:27.120 --> 00:38:28.650
Even as a working man,

558
00:38:28.820 --> 00:38:32.450
he could probably get an introduction to one of them or more if he needed it.

559
00:38:32.570 --> 00:38:35.760
These people were regarded as superior tradesman,

560
00:38:35.900 --> 00:38:39.280
not socially grand like the later London merchant bankers.

561
00:38:40.400 --> 00:38:40.961
As one example,

562
00:38:40.961 --> 00:38:45.760
Richard Arkwright with limited education and a background as a hairdresser

563
00:38:45.761 --> 00:38:46.594
and wigmaker,

564
00:38:47.260 --> 00:38:51.080
got considerable financial help from Wright and Co of Nottingham,

565
00:38:51.510 --> 00:38:54.239
a country bank founded in 1761.

566
00:38:55.540 --> 00:38:58.480
The result was that in the country banking system,

567
00:38:58.670 --> 00:39:03.440
many entrepreneurs obtained finance and a vast range of small businesses

568
00:39:03.441 --> 00:39:07.120
were able to discount their receivables, which is what most of them needed.

569
00:39:07.850 --> 00:39:12.560
No group think was possible, no fashionable ideas quelled the eccentric,

570
00:39:12.860 --> 00:39:14.760
the bankers were not fashionable.

571
00:39:15.290 --> 00:39:18.520
If an idea could work and could be begun on a modest scale,

572
00:39:18.520 --> 00:39:21.560
the chances were that it could be financed.

573
00:39:22.180 --> 00:39:27.160
The localism and pluralism of England's country banking system made it a

574
00:39:27.161 --> 00:39:29.520
major contributor to the Industrial Revolution,

575
00:39:29.560 --> 00:39:32.040
which has not been sufficiently recognized.

576
00:39:32.450 --> 00:39:37.440
If banking had still been concentrated in London as before 1760,

577
00:39:37.750 --> 00:39:42.600
it's most unlikely that the many small scale early industrialists in the

578
00:39:42.800 --> 00:39:44.600
provinces could have obtained finance.

579
00:39:47.170 --> 00:39:51.950
The 1760s also saw the emergence of five important industrialists

580
00:39:52.310 --> 00:39:56.469
whose careers, immensely assisted by the canals and country banks,

581
00:39:56.860 --> 00:40:00.750
launched Britain fully into industrialization in all its facets.

582
00:40:01.710 --> 00:40:03.830
They were: Josiah Wedgwood.

583
00:40:04.390 --> 00:40:08.870
The potter in business from 1759 who invented modern marketing

584
00:40:09.230 --> 00:40:12.630
techniques and for whom the Trent and Mersey canal was essential.

585
00:40:13.090 --> 00:40:16.710
His Etruria Works was built beside it's route.

586
00:40:18.100 --> 00:40:19.190
John Roebuck,

587
00:40:19.560 --> 00:40:24.469
founder of the Carron Iron Works in 1759 and he owned

588
00:40:24.800 --> 00:40:25.340
a colliery;

589
00:40:25.340 --> 00:40:29.950
patron of James Watt in the 1760s to attempt to pump out the colliery.

590
00:40:31.030 --> 00:40:33.950
Carron was a prime instigator of the Forth and Clyde Canal.

591
00:40:35.100 --> 00:40:36.310
John Wilkinson.

592
00:40:37.310 --> 00:40:42.110
Ironmaster from 1757 and inventor of the boring machine for

593
00:40:42.111 --> 00:40:44.670
steam engine cylinders in 1774.

594
00:40:46.030 --> 00:40:48.670
Early investor in the Staffordshire and Worcestershire canal;

595
00:40:49.430 --> 00:40:54.350
later founded several country banks and issued his own copper coinage.

596
00:40:56.590 --> 00:41:01.030
Richard Arkwright, patented his spinning frame in 1769.

597
00:41:01.450 --> 00:41:04.110
His early efforts funded by Wright and Company.

598
00:41:04.680 --> 00:41:09.630
He was the main financier of the 14 and a half mile Cromford canal to

599
00:41:09.631 --> 00:41:13.230
serve his Cromford mill. His son founded a country bank.

600
00:41:14.120 --> 00:41:18.550
Matthew Bolton substantial Birmingham manufacturer from

601
00:41:18.830 --> 00:41:22.110
1757, sponsor of the Birmingham canal,

602
00:41:22.150 --> 00:41:25.030
which had a branch to his Soho Manufactory.

603
00:41:25.430 --> 00:41:30.230
Later partnered with James Watt whose steam engines required cheap coal supplied

604
00:41:30.231 --> 00:41:32.830
by the canals. Overall,

605
00:41:32.980 --> 00:41:37.760
the sudden appearance of these industrial entrepreneurs indicates that Walter

606
00:41:38.150 --> 00:41:43.040
Rostow's takeoff of the Industrial Revolution occurred not in the 1780s

607
00:41:43.680 --> 00:41:46.960
as Rostow postulated, but nearly two decades earlier,

608
00:41:47.170 --> 00:41:51.960
largely sparked by the first canal boom and the country banks emergence.

609
00:41:52.530 --> 00:41:57.000
Whether the political transition of 1760 directly catalyzed

610
00:41:57.580 --> 00:42:00.840
industrialization can be questioned. More likely,

611
00:42:00.969 --> 00:42:03.800
it had been latent for half a century before this,

612
00:42:04.600 --> 00:42:06.640
had begun to appear in Queen Anne's time,

613
00:42:06.820 --> 00:42:11.239
but had been dampened by the takeover of the authoritarian and London

614
00:42:11.880 --> 00:42:13.480
centered Whigs in 1714.

615
00:42:14.219 --> 00:42:18.480
But there's no question the pluralistic Tory emergence assisted it.

616
00:42:18.820 --> 00:42:23.760
And key Tories like Gower and Newdigate rolled up their sleeves and got

617
00:42:24.120 --> 00:42:24.953
directly involved.

618
00:42:25.960 --> 00:42:30.800
There are two lessons for today to be learned from this podcast. First,

619
00:42:31.219 --> 00:42:36.040
infrastructure like Brindley's canals can be crucial to economic growth,

620
00:42:36.340 --> 00:42:41.239
but only if it revolutionizes existing economic patterns as Brindley's

621
00:42:41.240 --> 00:42:45.120
canals did increasing heavy goods transportation capacity 25

622
00:42:47.040 --> 00:42:47.790
fold.

623
00:42:47.790 --> 00:42:52.080
Spending a hundred billion pounds on a train that saves 20 minutes between

624
00:42:52.081 --> 00:42:54.960
London and Manchester is a complete waste of money.

625
00:42:55.960 --> 00:42:58.120
Building a bridge between Galloway and Ulster,

626
00:42:58.230 --> 00:43:02.320
connecting two parts of the same country that have never been connected before,

627
00:43:02.700 --> 00:43:04.880
may on the other hand, well be worthwhile.

628
00:43:06.670 --> 00:43:10.370
The second lesson is that innovation comes from small units,

629
00:43:10.371 --> 00:43:14.730
not large ones and needs a financial system geared to this reality.

630
00:43:15.760 --> 00:43:20.650
A financial system of beheamoth banks with a hundred thousand employees is

631
00:43:20.651 --> 00:43:23.650
a nominally private sector version of the old Soviet Gosplan.

632
00:43:24.340 --> 00:43:26.770
It will never finance anything new and useful.

633
00:43:27.550 --> 00:43:31.969
Nor will a system of hedge funds and private equity funds where they all follow

634
00:43:31.970 --> 00:43:34.650
the same fashionable and probably incorrect nostrums.

635
00:43:35.780 --> 00:43:40.330
We need a truly diverse financial system where the decision makers are not

636
00:43:40.331 --> 00:43:45.250
fashionable, but are local and are available for any ordinary person to contact.

637
00:43:46.180 --> 00:43:48.330
In today's world, that's a tough ask.

638
00:43:48.680 --> 00:43:53.090
It's perhaps the toughest to recover of all the Industrial Revolution's

639
00:43:53.091 --> 00:43:57.050
preconditions of growth, but it is worth making the attempt.

640
00:43:57.900 --> 00:43:58.733
Finally,

641
00:43:59.400 --> 00:44:04.170
I hope this podcast has convinced you that the emergence of the Industrial

642
00:44:04.171 --> 00:44:08.010
Revolution in Britain was indeed a Tory Story.

643
00:44:09.410 --> 00:44:11.370
Thank you very much for listening.

644
00:44:11.600 --> 00:44:16.130
That is the end of Tory Stories podcast number three.

